  "number": "9.1",
  "title": "Applications of Exponential Models Prep Activities",
  "body": " Applications of Exponential Models Prep Activities     Consider an item initially priced at $549.9, but which has had its price reduced by 10% several times in a row.     What is the change factor?      Find a formula for the item's new price after markdowns.      Use your formula to find the item's new price after 3 markdowns.      How many markdowns will it take for the item's price to be $300 or less? How do you know?       Cars lose value over time. This is called depreciation . Let's use information from carfax.com to analyze the change in the value of a brand new Subaru Crosstrek over time. Suppose the Crosstrek was purchased for $26,796.     The Carfax article says that the value of a new vehicle can drop by 20% after 1 year. Find the change factor, and use the change factor to estimate the value of Crosstrek in a year.      The Carfax article says that after the next four years, you can expect a car to lose about 15% of its value each year.     What is the change factor?      Estimate the value of the Crosstrek after 2, 3, 4, and 5 years using the change factors. Don't forget that the change factor is different for the 1st year!      Suppose that the car's value continues to depreciate at 15% per year. Find a formula for the value of the Crosstrek after years.       The Carfax article also says that 20% depreciation in the first year, followed by 15% depreciation for the next four years, is about the same as saying that a car is worth 40% of its purchase price after five years.     Is 40% the change factor or the percent change? Explain how you know.      If 40% is the change factor, find the percent change. If 40% is the pecent change, find the change factor.      Use the change factor to estimate the value of the Crosstrek after 5 years. How similar is your answer to your previous estimate?       You'll need to be able to do the following things for this lesson. Rate how confident you are on a scale of 1 - 5 (1 = not confident and 5 = very confident).     Skill or Concept: I can …  Rating from 1 to 5    Set up and evaluate exponential models given starting values and percent change.        "
